# Ubuntu Server SSH & GitHub Setup Guide

This guide documents the complete process of configuring an Ubuntu server to authenticate with GitHub using SSH. Once completed, you will be able to clone, pull, and push repositories without entering your GitHub username and password.

---

# Prerequisites

- Ubuntu Server
- Git installed
- GitHub account
- Terminal access

Verify Git is installed:

```bash
git --version
```

If Git is not installed:

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install git -y
```

---

# 1. Generate an SSH Key

Generate a new Ed25519 SSH key.

```bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your-email@example.com"
```

Example:

```bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "blessedtsiga19@gmail.com"
```

When prompted:

```
Enter file in which to save the key (/home/ubuntu/.ssh/id_ed25519):
```

### Recommended

Simply press **Enter** to accept the default location.

### OR

Specify a custom filename:

```
git_ssh
```

If using a custom filename, additional configuration is required later.

---

# 2. If You Saved the Key Outside ~/.ssh

Create the SSH directory if it does not already exist.

```bash
mkdir -p ~/.ssh
```

Move the keys.

```bash
mv git_ssh ~/.ssh/
mv git_ssh.pub ~/.ssh/
```

Set the correct permissions.

```bash
chmod 700 ~/.ssh
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/git_ssh
chmod 644 ~/.ssh/git_ssh.pub
```

---

# 3. Start the SSH Agent

```bash
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
```

Example output:

```
Agent pid 12345
```

---

# 4. Add the SSH Key

If using the default key:

```bash
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
```

If using a custom key:

```bash
ssh-add ~/.ssh/git_ssh
```

---

# 5. Configure SSH (Only Required for Custom Key Names)

If your key is not named `id_ed25519`, create an SSH configuration file.

```bash
nano ~/.ssh/config
```

Add:

```text
Host github.com
    HostName github.com
    User git
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/git_ssh
    IdentitiesOnly yes
```

Save the file and set permissions.

```bash
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/config
```

---

# 6. Copy Your Public Key

Display your public key.

```bash
cat ~/.ssh/git_ssh.pub
```

Or if using the default key:

```bash
cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
```

Copy the entire output.

Example:

```text
ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAI........ blessedtsiga19@gmail.com
```

---

# 7. Add the SSH Key to GitHub

1. Login to GitHub
2. Go to

```
Settings
    └── SSH and GPG Keys
```

3. Click

```
New SSH Key
```

4. Enter

Title:

```
Ubuntu Server
```

5. Paste the copied public key.

6. Click

```
Add SSH Key
```

---

# 8. Test the SSH Connection

```bash
ssh -T git@github.com
```

Expected output:

```
Hi <username>! You've successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.
```

---

# 9. Clone a Repository

Instead of HTTPS:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/username/repository.git
```

Use SSH:

```bash
git clone git@github.com:username/repository.git
```

Example:

```bash
git clone git@github.com:Blessed0702/Blessed_Tsiga_Portfolio.git
```

---

# 10. Existing Repository

If the repository already exists and was cloned using HTTPS, change it to SSH.

Check the current remote.

```bash
git remote -v
```

Example:

```
origin https://github.com/user/repo.git
```

Update it.

```bash
git remote set-url origin git@github.com:user/repo.git
```

Verify.

```bash
git remote -v
```

Expected:

```
origin git@github.com:user/repo.git
```

---

# 11. Configure Git Identity

Set your Git username.

```bash
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
```

Set your email.

```bash
git config --global user.email "your-email@example.com"
```

Verify.

```bash
git config --global --list
```

---

# 12. Common Git Commands

Clone

```bash
git clone git@github.com:user/repository.git
```

Check status

```bash
git status
```

Stage all files

```bash
git add .
```

Commit

```bash
git commit -m "Initial commit"
```

Push

```bash
git push origin main
```

Pull

```bash
git pull origin main
```

